â­ Improved IELTS Version (your ideas â†’ polished English)

I do not agree with the idea that schools should prioritise practical skills over academic subjects. In my opinion, a healthy education system requires a balance between the two. Many subjects simply cannot be learned through practice alone. For example, mathematics relies heavily on theoretical understanding; before applying formulas, students must first learn the underlying concepts. The same is true for physics and chemistry, where knowing the theory is essential before conducting any hands-on experiments, both for accuracy and safety. Even subjects that appear purely practical, such as sports or art, require a theoretical foundation. Athletes need to understand technique and body mechanics, and artists benefit from learning principles like colour theory or composition. Therefore, academic knowledge and practical skills complement each other rather than compete, and schools should maintain a balanced approach.


